Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Admission of Your Child to a School
Admission of Your Child to a School
* Do I have to register my child at a school?
* At what age can my child start Grade 1?
* When and where do I register my child?
* Can I register my child at any school even if it is not near my home or workplace?
* What do I need to know before registering my child?
* Which documents are required when making an application?
* What other documents are required if I am not a South African citizen?
* How do I know if my child has been accepted at the school?
* What can I do if my child is refused admission to a school?
Do I have to register my child at a school?
Yes, All children between the ages of seven and 15 should be registered.
At what age can my child start Grade 1?
Your child can only start Grade 1 if she/he will be turning seven during the first year of schooling.
In exceptional cases the Provincial Education Department may consider admission at an earlier age, and schools can advise you in this regard.
When and where do I register my child?
You may register your child at a school near your home or workplace between August and November in the year before the child start school.
Can I register my child at any school even if it is not near my home or workplace?
Yes, you can register your child at any public school.
However schools are expected to give first preference to children whose parents live or work near the school.
Once a school has reached capacity, they can refuse your child a place and put your child on a waiting list.
You must then register your child at another school that has an opening.
What do I need to know before registering my child?
You should be aware that your child does not have a guaranteed place at a school until you have registered the child at that school.
The principal of the school must give you the admissions policy of the school and explain it to you.
You should also ask which language/s are used for teaching at the school and decide if that is suitable for your child.
You should also find out what school fees the school charges.
If you cannot afford the fees, you should ask the principal or school official about how you can apply for full or partial exemption from paying the fees.
A public school may not administer any test for admission to a school.
A test may only be used for deciding which courses or programmes your child should do at the school.
You should ask to see the school's code of conduct and make sure that you are willing to sign it.
Which documents are required when making an application?
* Birth certificate or identity document of the child; and
* Immunisation card for the child; and
* Transfer card or last school report card for learners who have been to school previously.
(Note that baptismal certificates will not be regarded as proof of birth date.)
What other documents are required if I am not a South African citizen?
* Study permit; and
* Temporary or permanent residence permit form the Department of Home Affairs; or
* Evidence that you have applied for permission to stay in South Africa
How do I know if my child has been accepted at the school?
The Provincial Department of Education, through the school principal, must inform you of the outcome of your application.
What can I do if my child is refused admission to a school?
You can request a written explanation from the department, through the school principal.
If you are not satisfied with the reasons given for the decision, you may lodge a written appeal to the MEC for education in the province.
