School Fees
The school will ask you to pay school fees.
The amount is set a at a public meeting of the School Governing Body (SGB), which must be held each year an where parents vote on the amount of school fees to be paid.
However, if you cannot afford the required amount or can pay a lesser amount, you may write a letter to the SGB requesting full or part exemption from paying school fees.
The SGB will inform you of its decision.
A copy of the regulations dealing with school fees can be obtained from the school.
The school must assist you if you need help with your application for exemption.
* How do I appeal against the decision of the SGB?
* If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to the school?
* If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to any school activities or have his/her results withheld?
* Can I get financial assistance to pay school fees?
* How do I apply for grants to which I am entitled?
How do I appeal against the decision of the SGB?
You can lodge an appeal with the Provincial Head of the Education Department.
She/he will explain the reasons in writing if you were not granted exemption.
If it is determined that you can afford to pay the fees, and fail to do so, legal steps can be taken against you to ensure that you pay any outstanding fees.
If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to the school?
If exempted from paying school fees, can my child be refused access to any school activities or have his/her results withheld?
No. The school cannot withhold your child's results or exclude him/her any educational activity if you cannot afford to pay school fees.
Can I get financial assistance to pay school fees?
You can get partial or complete exemption from paying school fees based on your income.
You can increase your income by claiming grants that you may qualify for.
Two grants you might qualify for are:
* The Child Support Grant: This is given to a primary caregiver that cares for a child/children who are under the age of seven.
The caregiver can be the mother, father, grandparent, relative, friend or older brother/sister.
* The Foster Child Grant: This is for children who are placed with a person who is not the parnet, such as a grandparent.
A court must endorse the foster relationship.
How do I apply for grants to which I am entitled?
You should apply at the Welfare Office or your nearest Magistrate's Office.
The officials will ask you questions and fill in a form using your answers.
Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Governance
Governance
* What is a school governing body (SGB)?
* How do I get elected to represent other parents on the governing body?
* How do I get to know about the election process?
* What happens if I'm not elected onto the school governing body?
* Who makes the decision about school matters?
* Where can I lodge an objection against a decision or action?
What is a school governing body (SGB)?
An SGB is a structure that governs the school.
It stands in a position of trust towards the school.
It is made up of the principal, elected representatives of educators, non-educator staff, parents and learners, in the case of secondary schools.
The SGB can also select persons in the community who have special skills to be non-voting members of the SGB.
How do I get elected to represent other parents on the governing body?
You can represent other parents on a governing body if you are nominated and voted for by parents.
The SGB is elected for a three-year period.
You can stand at the next election.
As soon as your last child leaves the school, you must resign your seat, as you no longer have any rights on the SGB.
Parents can be re-elected as long as they have children in the school.
How do I get to know about the election process?
The principal/SGB of the school is required by law to provide all parents with information about the election of parents onto the governing body.
You should vote in each SGB election.
What happens if I'm not elected onto the school governing body?
Even if you are not elected onto the school governing body, you should support the school's SGB in its work and you must respond to written notices calling for a response.
You have the RIGHT to be involved in the affairs of the school through attending meetings of parents or other meetings organised by the school, including the SGB's Annual General Meeting.
The school must give you at least 30 days notice before this meeting is to be held.
At this meeting the SGB must present its budget and annual financial report.
The school must present a report concerning its activities at least once a year.
You also have the RIGHT to be consulted by the educators or the principal about the schooling activities of our child.
The principal and the educators at the school must notify you in good time and regularly about the well-being, behaviour, attendance and learning progress of you child.
You must also be informed and represent your child at any disciplinary proceedings against your child in terms of the school's Code of Conduct.
Who makes the decision about school matters?
The Head of the Provincial Education Department, through the principal, takes all decisions about education in the school.
You should be informed about these decisions and have the right to information concerning the school and your child's education.
Your school must also have a Code of Conduct.
You have the right to be consulted regarding the preparation and amendment of the Code of Conduct.
Where can I lodge an objection against a decision or action?
You can lodge an objection against a decision or action of:
* an educator, with the principal;
* a principal, with the Head of the Education Department in the province;
* a representative council of learners member, with the school governing body; and,
* a school governing body member, with the MEC or Head of Department.
Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt Language of Learning and Teaching
Language of Learning and Teaching
* What does the Language-in-Education Policy say?
* Will my child not be disadvantaged by being taught in a language other than English?
* Who decides on the language of learning and teaching?
* Does my child have options regarding the language of learning and teaching in a school?
What does the Language-in-Education Policy say?
The Department's Language-in-Education Policy encourages learners to learn more that one language.
It also encourages them to use the language that they best understand as the language of learning and teaching.
They can learn other languages as subjects or add other languages as languages of instruction.
Will my child not be disadvantaged by being taught in a language other than English?
Learning through the home language during the first years of formal schooling ensures a solid foundation for future learning, as well as the acquisition of new/other languages.
Who decides on the language of learning and teaching?
The SGB must decide on the language of learning and teaching used in a school.
The language used will depend on the preference of the majority of learners in the school and the ability of the school to teach in the preferred language.
In addition, the SGB needs to indicate how it will promote multilingualism in the school.
Does my child have options regarding the language of learning and teaching in a school?
Each learner must, upon registration at a school, indicate the preferred language of learning and teaching.
Any of our 11 languages may be indicated as the language of learning and teaching in a public school.
Where there are more than 30 children requesting a particular language, the school must make an effort to offer tuition in that language.
Home > Publications > Public Information > A > Rights and Responsibilities of Parents - A Public School Policy Guide &gt You Have the Following Responsibilities as a Parent
You Have the Following Responsibilities as a Parent
* How should I contribute towards the development of my child's school?
* What role can I play in supporting the learning process of my child?
* How can I keep abreast of the developments at the school?
How should I contribute towards the development of my child's school?
As a parent, you have a responsibility to contribute towards the development of the school by rendering services to the school.
This may include making yourself available to participate in the activities of the school such as the maintenance of school property, auditing of financial statements, managing sports events, helping manage school trips etc.
What role can I play in supporting the learning process of my child?
Your child is in the custody of the school staff when she/he is at the school.
The school staff can successfully carryout their teaching responsibilities if they receive the support of the parents.
As a parent you have the responsibility to:
* make sure that your child attends school regularly;
* assist with the discipline of your child;
* assist the school in promoting a culture of mutual respect and tolerance;
* monitor your child's educational progress;
* ensure that she/he completes her/his homework;
* liase with the school staff; and
* respond to school notices calling for responses.
How can I keep abreast of developments at the school?
Parents of learners must take responsibility for attending school meetings that are organised for them.
The SGB is legally bound to report to the parents of learners at the school form time to time, and should keep parents informed about issues that affect them.
You have the right to request any additional information that is of interest to you from the SGB and the principal of the school.
The SGB or principal must supply this information, or tell you in writing why they cannot give the information.
