The Garden Route
Slavery was widely practised in the Southern Cape in the 18th and early 19th centuries.
The VOC outposts of which Outeniqualand and Plettenberg Bay formed a part, as well as the farms of settlers, all have a slave history.
Many villages and towns that originated as missions have a fascinating history involving both slaves and freed slaves.
Caledon Square, later Victoria Square (Courtenay Street) Originally known as the market place, Victoria Square is now a Garden of Remembrance.
It was flanked to the north by the Drostdy and to the east by the jail.
Until 1834, this is where salves were auctioned.
